<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level CREATE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager` UNCONDITIONAL create access
    on records of the `x_casemgmt_case_task` custom table inside the scoped
    application `x_casemgmt`. This is the CREATE companion to the case_manager
    read / write / delete ACLs on the case_task table (whose granting ACLs are
    materialized by the sibling files
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml,
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml, and
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_manager.xml). Together those four files
    realize the AAP Section 0.5.6 manager row mirrored at the case_task table
    level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/
    x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml" ("Mirror ACL pattern at task level"):
    "x_casemgmt_case_manager : Create=Yes, Read=All, Write=All, Delete=Yes."

    Of the four CRUD operations, CREATE is the "entry-point" privilege for
    the case_task domain: it is the operation that brings new x_casemgmt_case_task
    rows into existence so that every downstream privilege (read, write, delete)
    and every downstream Flow Designer state-machine guard - in particular the
    AAP Section 0.5.5 In Progress -> Resolved transition rule "All linked
    x_casemgmt_case_task records have status = Closed" - has task records to act
    upon. Without this ACL no x_casemgmt_case_manager-tier user could file a new
    task against an existing case from the internal native form view, and the
    manager would be reduced to a read/write/delete-only role on task records
    originating elsewhere (specifically: agent-originated tasks). That outcome
    would directly contradict the AAP Section 0.5.6 "Create=Yes" cell for the
    manager row mirrored to the case_task table, and it would also break the
    operational pattern in which a manager opens a case, immediately decomposes
    it into one or more child tasks (Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other -
    per ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml), and routes those tasks to
    the appropriate case_agent assignees.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_manager row, mirrored at the
        case_task table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at task level"):
            | Role                    | Create | Read | Write | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All  |  All  |  Yes   |
        This file authors the single "Create = Yes" cell of the manager row
        for the case_task table. The "All" Read cell is authored by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml; the "All" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml; the "Yes" Delete cell
        by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_manager.xml. Each row of the
        ACL matrix maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML files - this per-cell
        granularity is what lets the Update Set add or remove role privileges
        independently without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles create coverage on case_task:
            - case_manager: Create=Yes -> THIS FILE
            - case_agent:   Create=Yes -> ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_agent.xml
                                          (also unconditional; per AAP both
                                           manager and agent can create tasks)
            - case_viewer:  Create=No  -> deliberate absence of any
                                          x_casemgmt_case_task_create_viewer.xml
                                          (deny-by-default)
        Together these three facts implement the user prompt's contract that
        managers (operational oversight tier) and agents (operational worker
        tier) can both originate task records, while the lowest-privilege
        viewer (audit / compliance / supervisor tier) cannot. The agent's
        create is paired with a corresponding read/write _agent_assigned
        scoping that limits the agent's subsequent visibility of and edits
        to case_task rows to those whose parent case is "Assigned only" to
        the agent (per ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml
        and ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml); the
        manager has no such post-create restriction (manager Read=All,
        Write=All on case_task per the sibling read/write ACLs).
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
             case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has
             full access."
        The clause "case_manager has full access" requires that the manager
        role be able to perform every CRUD operation on the case_task table;
        of the four operations, CREATE is the operation that brings new rows
        into existence so the others have something to act upon. This ACL
        satisfies the create operation half of "full access" for the task
        domain; the parallel read / write / delete halves are satisfied by
        the three sibling manager ACLs on case_task.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 2 - Workflow):
            "All state transitions enforced for both case types - Invalid
             transitions return blocking error; task-closure check blocks
             Resolved transition."
        The "task-closure check" here refers to the AAP Section 0.5.5 rule
        that "In Progress -> Resolved" requires "All linked x_casemgmt_case_task
        records have status = Closed" - implemented in
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml and the helper
        Script Include
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml. Validating
        Gate 2 end-to-end requires the test driver to be able to attach at
        least one open task to a case and then attempt a Resolved transition
        to confirm the verbatim blocking error message "All tasks must be
        closed before resolving this case." (AAP Section 0.7.4) is surfaced.
        The demo manager
        (../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml) is the
        natural driver for this validation, and THIS ACL is what authorizes
        the manager-as-task-creator step of that validation flow.
      - Section 0.7.4 (Other User-Provided Rules) - "Tasks created, linked
        to cases, assigned, and closed - case resolution blocked until all
        linked tasks are closed." This success-criterion bullet implies
        authenticated case_manager users must be able to create tasks via
        the internal native form view; THIS ACL is what makes that path
        permitted at the platform's record-level authorization layer.
      - Section 0.7.4 (Minimum demo-data thresholds) - the seed data plan
        in AAP Section 0.4.1 calls for "demo tasks; at least one open and
        one closed task on selected demo cases" so the resolved-transition
        gate can be exercised against the demo dataset. The seed itself
        (../scripts/seed_demo_data.js, ../seed-data/tasks/
        x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml) runs as platform admin and bypasses
        per-role ACLs via admin_overrides=true, but the post-seed manual
        smoke test of the Gate 2 task-closure rule requires a logged-in
        manager to create at least one fresh open task during validation -
        which is what THIS ACL authorizes.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level CREATE binding for the
        highest-tier scoped role on the task domain and is one of the
        declarative facts the platform's sys_security_acl evaluator
        consumes when authorizing a row insert at runtime against the
        case_task table.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "ApplicationRolesConfig + RolesPrivilegesService +
        URL-based privilege metadata -> scoped roles + ACLs." In ArkCase
        the equivalent of THIS file would have been a single entry in the
        rolesToPrivileges map binding the manager-equivalent role
        (e.g., ROLE_CASE_MANAGER) to a task-create privilege identifier
        such as `acm-task-create` or `acm-task-add`, evaluated at HTTP
        request time by AcmPluginUrlPrivilege against the POST verb on
        the task REST endpoint. The ServiceNow target replaces both the
        map binding and the URL-privilege evaluator with this single
        declarative ACL record; the platform's sys_security_acl engine
        handles the role-membership check, the empty-condition evaluation,
        and the admin-override logic that ArkCase implemented through
        hand-written Java code (see acm-services/acm-service-users plus
        the admin-plugin Java REST controllers under
        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/.../web/api/).

    Why <advanced>false</advanced> (no scripted condition for manager create):
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6, the case_manager role's privileges on the
      case_task table are unconditional ("Yes", "All", "Full access") -
      there is no "Assigned only" or other row-level filter for the
      manager tier. The manager is intentionally NOT scoped to a subset
      of tasks; they have org-wide create authority because their job
      function is to originate, triage, route, prioritize, escalate, and
      close cases - and child tasks - across all assignment boundaries.
      Additionally, the create operation has no `current` record to
      evaluate row-level predicates against - the row is being inserted
      at the moment the ACL fires, so any "Assigned only"-style check is
      logically impossible at create time (assigned_to on the
      freshly-instantiated task record skeleton is typically null until
      the manager populates it, and the parent case reference is
      typically populated but the task itself does not yet exist for
      "Assigned only" semantics to be meaningful). For these two reasons -
      design intent and logical inapplicability - the manager create ACL
      on case_task is unconditional:
        - <advanced>false</advanced>      - no scripted condition
        - <condition/>                    - empty encoded query (no row filter)
        - <script/>                       - empty server-side script
      With no condition and no script, the ACL evaluates to "permit" for
      any caller who carries the x_casemgmt_case_manager role. This is the
      correct semantic for the AAP's "manager has full create" requirement
      on the task domain. Setting advanced=true with an empty script body
      would be functionally equivalent but stylistically incorrect - the
      ServiceNow convention is to reserve advanced=true for ACLs that
      actually carry a scripted body (see, for contrast,
      ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml and
      ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml where
      advanced=true and the script encodes the parent-case "Assigned
      only" check that walks from the case_task row up to its parent
      x_casemgmt_case row to evaluate
      `current.case.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() ||
      gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.case.assigned_group)`).

    Why CREATE is granted to manager unconditionally (design rationale):
      - Operational origination: managers must be able to file new tasks
        against existing cases on behalf of agents (when an agent flags a
        case for a sub-task they cannot themselves field), to record
        retro-active investigative steps during audit reviews, to seed
        test / demo data while validating the application, and to
        mass-decompose newly-opened cases into the standard intake
        checklist of Investigation / Review / Follow-up tasks per
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml. Restricting manager
        create on case_task would defeat one of the primary use-cases of
        the manager role, which is to be the "complete" case-management
        persona who originates and orchestrates work across the case AND
        task domains.
      - Workflow gate enabler: per AAP Section 0.5.5 the In Progress ->
        Resolved transition is gated by "All linked x_casemgmt_case_task
        records have status = Closed". Validating that gate end-to-end
        requires the operator to be able to attach AT LEAST ONE task to
        a case and observe the gate fire when a Resolved attempt is made
        while that task is still open. The manager (the only role with
        Resolved -> Closed authority per AAP Section 0.5.5) is the
        natural validator; THIS ACL is what authorizes the prerequisite
        task-creation step of that validation.
      - Demo-data lifecycle: the seed script ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
        creates demo tasks "at least one open and one closed task on
        selected demo cases" (AAP Section 0.4.1 / Section 0.7.4). The
        script itself runs as platform admin (so admin_overrides=true
        bypasses every per-role ACL during seeding), but the manual
        round-trip-verify path that exercises ../docs/validation-gates.md
        Gate 2 has a logged-in demo manager create at least one fresh
        task to confirm the form, mandatory-field validation,
        auto-numbering (per ../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task.xml),
        and the parent-case Reference field (per
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_case.xml) all work end-to-end.
        THIS ACL is what authorizes that manager-as-task-creator session.
      - Manager and agent both originate tasks: per AAP Section 0.5.6,
        both the case_manager and case_agent roles have Create=Yes on
        case_task. This ACL realizes the manager half of that pair; the
        sibling ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_agent.xml realizes the
        agent half. Both roles need to originate tasks because:
          (a) Managers decompose cases into work items as described
              above.
          (b) Agents working a case discover sub-investigations (e.g., a
              witness is identified mid-Investigation that warrants its
              own Follow-up task) and must be able to record those
              sub-investigations as new tasks against the case they
              already work on. The agent's create is unconditional in
              the same sense as the manager's: at create time there is
              no `current` row to evaluate "Assigned only" against, so
              both manager and agent get binary role-based create
              authority. The asymmetry between the two roles is enforced
              POST-create by the read/write _agent_assigned scoping on
              the agent (siblings *_read_agent_assigned and
              *_write_agent_assigned), which limits the agent to viewing
              and editing only those tasks whose PARENT CASE is assigned
              to them.
      - No "Assigned only" semantic at create time: as noted above, the
        platform binds `current` to a freshly-instantiated record
        skeleton with the caller's POSTed field values at create-ACL
        evaluation time. assigned_to on that skeleton is typically null
        (or whatever the form defaulted it to), and the parent `case`
        reference is populated but the task itself does not yet exist as
        a row to apply "Assigned only" against. Any "Assigned only"-style
        predicate would therefore either always-permit or always-deny
        based on those nulls / unresolved references - neither of which
        expresses any meaningful authorization rule. The AAP design
        pattern in Section 0.4.3 reserves the "Assigned only" predicate
        for read/write ACLs (siblings
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml carry the
        scripted condition); create on case_task is correctly modeled as
        a binary role check.

    What governs the row AFTER the manager creates it:
      The newly-inserted x_casemgmt_case_task row is governed downstream by:
        (a) The dictionary defaults established in
            ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_status.xml, which set the
            default status to "Open" so any newly-inserted row that does
            not explicitly set status lands in the Open state (per AAP
            Section 0.5.7 the case_task.status choice values are Open /
            In Progress / Closed; Open is the canonical entry state).
        (b) The dictionary defaults in
            ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_case.xml combined with
            ../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task.xml, which
            auto-assign a unique TASK-format number and bind the task to
            its parent case via the Reference field (per AAP Section
            0.5.7 the `case` field is "Reference -> x_casemgmt_case
            Mandatory"). The Update Set apply-time order ensures
            ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml exists before this ACL
            fires for the first time, so the Reference resolves cleanly.
        (c) The validate_resolved_transition subflow
            (../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml) and its
            invoker Script Include
            (../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml),
            which on every parent-case status update query
            x_casemgmt_case_task by case=current.sys_id AND status!=Closed;
            if any rows are returned the In Progress -> Resolved
            transition is blocked with the verbatim error
            "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case." (AAP
            Section 0.7.4). The newly-inserted task is the very record
            that participates in that query.
        (d) The case_task table-level read/write/delete ACLs for each
            role, which govern what each role can do with the new task
            after it lands:
              - manager: read all (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml),
                write all (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml),
                delete (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_manager.xml)
              - agent:   read assigned (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml),
                write assigned (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml),
                no delete (deliberate absence)
              - viewer:  read all (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_viewer.xml),
                no write, no delete (deliberate absence)
      In short: this ACL is the gate to bring the task row into existence;
      the four artifacts above are what shape its initial state and govern
      its subsequent lifecycle. The composition of (this ACL) + (the
      manager read/write/delete ACLs on case_task) + (the parent-case
      Resolved-transition gate) is what gives the manager the complete
      authority to originate, orchestrate, and finally close out tasks
      across the entire case lifecycle.

    Why a separate file per role (instead of one create ACL with both roles):
      ServiceNow allows multiple roles in a single <roles> field as a
      comma-separated list, and that pattern technically also satisfies
      the AAP. However, the established convention in this Update Set
      (and in industry practice for scoped applications) is one ACL
      record per (table, operation, role) triple. Reasons:
        - Single-responsibility: each ACL record encodes exactly one
          authorization fact; if the AAP later removes case_manager's
          create privilege on case_task (e.g., to enforce a stricter
          "manager opens cases, agents originate tasks" policy at a
          future iteration), the change is a single-file deletion with
          no risk of accidentally also revoking case_agent's create
          privilege.
        - Auditability: the file inventory under ../acl/ becomes a
          self-documenting matrix - the presence or absence of a file
          named x_casemgmt_<table>_<operation>_<role>.xml is the answer
          to "does role X have privilege Y on table Z?". Reviewers can
          inspect the AAP matrix in Section 0.5.6 and verify in seconds
          that every "Yes" cell has a corresponding XML file and every
          "No" cell has a corresponding ABSENCE.
        - Update Set diff clarity: when the Update Set is re-imported on
          a fresh PDI per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7, each ACL is a discrete
          row in the preview screen, making it easy to spot that
          case_manager's create privilege on case_task was installed
          (alongside case_agent's) versus a single combined row that
          would obscure the role membership.
      The companion ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_agent.xml file
      authors the case_agent half of the Create=Yes pair using the same
      per-role-per-operation pattern.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the
        property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. The class declares the
        constant `ROLES_TO_PRIVILEGES_PROP_KEY = "application.rolesToPrivileges"`
        and exposes the map via `@MapValue(value = "application.rolesToPrivileges")
        getRolesToPrivileges()`. In that model, a "manager-equivalent"
        role (e.g., ROLE_CASE_MANAGER) would have been associated with
        a task-create privilege identifier such as `acm-task-create` or
        `acm-task-add`. The ServiceNow target replaces this map-based
        privilege association with declarative, scoped record-level ACLs -
        this XML record is the direct equivalent of one cell in the map:
        the (case_manager, CREATE) pairing for the case_task table.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        `addRolesPrivileges(...)`, `removeRolesPrivileges(...)`, plus
        the role-name normalization step that uppercased the role,
        replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods with
        double-underscores, and prepended the `ROLE_` prefix from
        RolePrivilegesConstants). The service held injected dependencies
        on `UserDao`, `ApplicationRolesConfig`,
        `ApplicationPrivilegesConfig`,
        `ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig`,
        `ConfigurationPropertyService`,
        `CollectionPropertiesConfigurationService`, and
        `FunctionalAccessService` - a complex Spring/JPA stack that
        managed the role <-> privilege relationship at runtime. All of
        this Java service surface is replaced in the ServiceNow target
        by the platform's built-in sys_security_acl evaluator and by
        static role names declared in scope-prefixed sys_user_role
        records (the case_manager role is declared in
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml; this ACL
        references it by literal name in the <roles> field). Notably,
        ArkCase's `retrievePrivilegesByRole(roleName)` method paginated
        through the rolesToPrivileges map to return a role's privileges -
        the ServiceNow analog is the platform's "Roles" related list on
        sys_security_acl, which is automatically derived from the
        <roles> field of every ACL record like THIS one; no explicit
        query service is needed.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package source =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case_task (NOT the OOB
        `task` table or any other global table), and <roles> references
        the scoped role x_casemgmt_case_manager. There are zero global
        writes from this file. Per AAP Section 0.3.2 "Global scope
        changes of any kind" are explicitly prohibited.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name
        / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The <sys_id>
        below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key (32-char
        lowercase hex MD5 of the canonical string
        "x_casemgmt_case_task.create.case_manager", a stable canonical
        identifier for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to
        any other record. Computing the sys_id deterministically
        guarantees the ACL is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs
        and round-trip Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7,
        and matches the sibling-ACL convention:
          - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml uses
            MD5("x_casemgmt_case_task.read.case_manager")
            = c97e1d074ba86bf16b3a10cb4851e562
          - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml uses
            MD5("x_casemgmt_case_task.write.case_manager")
            = e71dc6760bcbc259019f5fc18442c014
          - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_manager.xml uses
            MD5("x_casemgmt_case_task.delete.case_manager")
            = 6c1bd40bcab435a7951bfeb732cd90e0
          - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_agent.xml uses
            MD5("x_casemgmt_case_task.create.case_agent")
            = e0d5a22fa8de097d5b478125eb6dfc67
          - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml uses
            MD5("x_casemgmt_case.create.case_manager")
            = 225e62a69110cad11ec91010e2a8b380
          - this file uses MD5("x_casemgmt_case_task.create.case_manager")
            = 306ca879b1115cbe4f023af16b0417b2
        The canonical-string convention is "<table>.<operation>.<role>"
        where <role> uses the role's short suffix (case_manager,
        case_agent, case_viewer) so the strings remain stable even if
        the casemgmt placeholder is later substituted for the concrete
        PDI-assigned scope id (the substitution applies uniformly across
        every reference in this file at Update Set apply time and does
        not affect the canonical-string-to-sys_id mapping).
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case_task`
        with NO dot. ServiceNow's create operation has no concept of
        "create this specific column" - field-level ACLs apply only to
        read/write/none. There are no field-level ACLs on case_task at
        all in this Update Set (in contrast to the case table, which
        carries field-level ACLs on assigned_group and assigned_agent
        per ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml); the
        case_task table's column-level governance is fully expressed by
        the table-level ACLs alone. The <type>record</type> field below
        confirms this is a row-level (table-level) ACL, not a
        UI/REST/SOAP-flavored ACL.
      - Operation = create: corresponds exactly to the "Create = Yes"
        cell in the AAP matrix for the case_manager role mirrored to the
        case_task table. There is deliberately no field-level create
        restriction for any role on any column; field-level ACLs in
        ServiceNow apply only to read and write operations.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or seed
        scoped data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js script runs as admin to populate
        demo cases AND demo tasks). It does NOT widen case_manager
        privileges - non-admin managers see exactly what this ACL
        permits, which is unconditional table-level create on case_task.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is empty;
        no row-level filter applies (and none is meaningful pre-insert).
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform skips
        it because advanced=false.
      - description: a single-sentence operator-readable summary of what
        this ACL grants, mirroring the description style of the sibling
        manager ACLs. The description is surfaced in the System Security
        > Access Control list view and aids platform administrators
        during ACL audits without their needing to re-read the full
        canonical comment block above.
      - sys_class_name = sys_security_acl: matches the table name
        declared in <record_update table="sys_security_acl">; this is
        the ServiceNow convention for self-identifying record class on
        polymorphic-able tables (sys_security_acl itself is not currently
        polymorphic but the class name field is included for forward
        compatibility and for Update Set serialization completeness).
      - sys_created_by / sys_updated_by = admin: synthetic audit values
        that do not carry any PII; the literal "admin" string is the
        ServiceNow built-in admin user name (looked up by user_name at
        apply time; no admin sys_id literal is hardcoded). Per AAP
        Section 0.3.2 "PII or real customer data" is prohibited and
        synthetic-only data is required; the "admin" account name is a
        ServiceNow platform built-in, not customer data.
      - sys_created_on / sys_updated_on = 2025-01-01 00:00:00: a fixed
        sentinel timestamp that ensures byte-stable Update Set XML output
        across re-exports of the same scoped application; this avoids
        spurious diffs in version control when the only "change" would
        be the auto-updated timestamp. This convention matches every
        sibling ACL file in this directory.
      - sys_mod_count = 0: starts at zero on first apply; the platform
        increments it on subsequent updates after the Update Set commits.

    Difference from sibling ACLs - quick reference:
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml (manager READ on
      case_task):
        - <operation>     create             vs read
        - <sys_id>        306ca879b1115cbe4f023af16b0417b2
                                             vs c97e1d074ba86bf16b3a10cb4851e562
        - <sys_update_name> *_create_manager vs *_read_manager
        - <description>                      differs in operation wording
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml (manager WRITE on
      case_task):
        - <operation>     create             vs write
        - <sys_id>        306ca879b1115cbe4f023af16b0417b2
                                             vs e71dc6760bcbc259019f5fc18442c014
        - <sys_update_name> *_create_manager vs *_write_manager
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_manager.xml (manager DELETE on
      case_task):
        - <operation>     create             vs delete
        - <sys_id>        306ca879b1115cbe4f023af16b0417b2
                                             vs 6c1bd40bcab435a7951bfeb732cd90e0
        - <sys_update_name> *_create_manager vs *_delete_manager
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_agent.xml (agent CREATE on
      case_task - same operation, different role):
        - <roles>         x_casemgmt_case_manager
                                             vs x_casemgmt_case_agent
        - <sys_id>        306ca879b1115cbe4f023af16b0417b2
                                             vs e0d5a22fa8de097d5b478125eb6dfc67
        - <sys_update_name> *_create_manager vs *_create_agent
        - <description>                      refers to manager  vs agent
        Both files have advanced=false, empty condition, and empty
        script because both manager and agent have unconditional create
        on case_task per the AAP matrix (the AAP intentionally puts
        manager and agent in the same Create=Yes bucket because both
        internal-tier roles need to be able to originate tasks; only
        the audit-tier viewer is denied create). The two files are
        functionally parallel and together give the manager and agent
        roles identical create authority on x_casemgmt_case_task; the
        post-create access asymmetry between the two roles is enforced
        by the read/write _agent_assigned scoping on the agent.
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml (manager CREATE on
      case - same operation, same role, different table):
        - <name>          x_casemgmt_case_task
                                             vs x_casemgmt_case
        - <sys_name>      x_casemgmt_case_task
                                             vs x_casemgmt_case
        - <sys_id>        306ca879b1115cbe4f023af16b0417b2
                                             vs 225e62a69110cad11ec91010e2a8b380
        - <sys_update_name> *_case_task_create_manager
                                             vs *_case_create_manager
        - <description>                      references the case_task
                                             vs case table semantic
        Both files have advanced=false, empty condition, and empty
        script because both case and case_task tables grant
        unconditional create to case_manager per the AAP matrix. The
        two files are intentionally parallel: this is the explicit
        "mirror ACL pattern at task level" mandated by AAP Section
        0.5.1 row "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/
        x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml".
      All other XML elements are identical between the manager-tier
      ACLs; the deterministic sys_id and the operation/role/table triplet
      are the defining differences. This is intentional: the homogeneity
      of the per-cell ACL files is what makes the matrix-style review
      tractable for both human auditors and automated diff tools.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app
          record; establishes the case-management application that owns
          this ACL)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (resolves
          <name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name> by table name lookup at apply
          time; without the table being present first, this ACL would
          be orphaned and the Update Set preview would error)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles> by role name lookup at
          apply time)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
          (the demo manager's create access during round-trip
          verification depends on this ACL being applied first; the
          seed step that grants the demo manager their role makes the
          create privilege effective)
        - ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml (demo task
          rows inserted by the seed pass benefit from this ACL being in
          place if any seed runs under the demo manager's identity
          context; the seed_demo_data.js script itself runs as admin so
          admin_overrides=true bypasses this ACL during seeding, but
          post-seed manager-side smoke tests against the demo dataset
          depend on this ACL being applied)
        - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml
          (the validate_resolved_transition subflow queries
          x_casemgmt_case_task to enforce the In Progress -> Resolved
          gate; the gate is only meaningful if managers can create
          tasks against cases - which this ACL authorizes)
      The deny-by-default sibling pair that this file works with:
        - There is NO equivalent "deny" ACL needed for any role;
          ServiceNow ACLs are deny-by-default. A user without the
          case_manager role (and without case_agent) cannot insert rows
          on x_casemgmt_case_task regardless of any per-role ACL state.
          Specifically: the case_viewer role cannot create tasks
          because there is NO x_casemgmt_case_task_create_viewer.xml
          file in this folder - the absence is the deny.
        - x_casemgmt_case_task_create_viewer.xml (DOES NOT EXIST -
          by design)
      Adding a viewer-create file would VIOLATE the AAP Section 0.5.6
      matrix and MUST NOT be done by any future agent.

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention
    (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); ServiceNow
    Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id
    must be concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped
    application. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against
    the `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto
    fresh PDIs.
-->
